#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""verify-chain — Rung 3 of design/MAINT-GPG-TRUST-LAYER.md §4 ("the anchored ledger: kernel delta s26
+ the signed head"). Walks THIS world's `row_hash` chain (kernel/lineage/s26-row-hash-chain.sql)
end to end and reports the FIRST row, if any, whose stored `row_hash` disagrees with a fresh
recomputation — proof that no row between the world's genesis seed and that point was
retroactively altered.

NO CANONICALIZATION LOGIC LIVES HERE (ADR-0012 P1/P7). The recomputation is done by Postgres
itself, via the SAME `compute_row_hash()` SQL function the s26 insert trigger calls — this script
issues one read-only query and reports what it returns; it never re-implements "what a row's
content means" a second time in Python. Two independent implementations of one canonicalization
is exactly the "two writers of one truth" cancer s26's own header names and forecloses; this
script honors that by construction, not by discipline.

TAIL-DELETION WITNESS (tracker item `s26-tail-deletion-witness`, kernel delta
kernel/lineage/s27-chain-high-water.sql, decision row 192): the row_hash chain alone proves no
row BETWEEN the genesis seed and the current head was altered, but is structurally blind to a
TAIL deletion — deleting the highest-id row leaves no later row whose predecessor lookup
depended on it, so the walk above reports INTACT over a silently-shortened chain
(seen-red/s26-row-hash-chain-deletion/'s own closure statement, case c). This is the literature's
TRUNCATION ATTACK against an append-only log; s27's `:kern.chain_high_water` witness — a one-row,
kernel-side monotonic high-water mark, bumped in the SAME transaction as each ledger insert so a
rollback cannot leave it ahead of a row that never durably existed — closes the gap for the
common case: when it is present, this script compares the WALKED max id against it. witness >
walked max means rows are missing from the tail, reported as the distinct verdict
TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT (exit 3, never conflated with a row_hash BROKEN result). A pre-s27 world
(no `chain_high_water` relation) degrades honestly to WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE — never a false
"suspect", never a crash. This witness is TRIPWIRE-grade, exactly as s26's own row_hash chain is:
it does not defend against a schema-owner adversary who rewrites the witness table alongside the
ledger (same LIMITS register — see s27's own header); the prior-arted closing move for that
adversary remains the externally-held, human-signed chain head (design/MAINT-GPG-TRUST-LAYER.md
§4, Ceremony 3). The bigserial sequence's `last_value` is reported alongside as SECONDARY,
EXPLAIN-NOT-FAIL corroboration only (never affects the exit code): `nextval()` is
non-transactional and survives a rolled-back insert, so a bare last_value-vs-ledger comparison
would false-positive on any world that ever rolled back a write — s27's own header explains why
the table-backed witness, not the sequence, is the PRIMARY signal.

MODES:
  ./verify-chain             — walk the whole chain, report the first break (if any), then (when
                               the row_hash chain itself reports INTACT or EMPTY) compare the
                               walked max id against the s27 chain_high_water witness. Exit 0 if
                               intact and the witness agrees (or is honestly UNAVAILABLE on a
                               pre-s27 world); 1 if the row_hash chain itself is BROKEN (the first
                               break's row id, stored vs expected hash, and total break count are
                               all printed — never an umbrella "chain broken" with no specifics);
                               3 if the row_hash chain is otherwise clean but the witness reports
                               TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT (rows are missing from the tail — a class the
                               row_hash chain alone cannot see, per seen-red/
                               s26-row-hash-chain-deletion/'s own closure statement); 4 on the
                               anomalous WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER case (the witness itself appears to
                               have been lowered, which should never happen under correct
                               operation — see s27-chain-high-water.sql's own header); 5 on
                               CANNOT-VERIFY (added 2026-07-13, tracker item
                               `verify-chain-error-conflation`) — a capability-check query itself
                               FAILED TO EXECUTE (connection refused, auth failed, timeout, or a
                               real query bug), so this world's row_hash/high-water status could
                               not be determined at all, and was NEVER read as the honest,
                               unrelated "pre-s26/pre-s27, nothing to verify" case (exit 0/
                               UNAVAILABLE/WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE) that a benign schema-absence
                               produces. Concretely: exit 5 fires either when
                               `has_row_hash_layer()`'s own query fails (top-level status
                               CANNOT-VERIFY) or when `has_high_water_layer()`'s/
                               `read_high_water()`'s query fails after the row_hash chain itself
                               already reported INTACT/EMPTY (witness-level status ERROR) — a
                               verifier that could not connect must say so loudly, never shrug and
                               call it "nothing to verify here". Exit codes 1/3/4/5 are
                               deliberately DISTINCT so a caller can tell "interior tamper" from
                               "tail truncation" from "witness anomaly" from "could not even look"
                               without parsing prose. Exit 6 (added with kernel delta s43,
                               kernel/lineage/s43-typed-verdict-write-boundary.sql Element 5)
                               is the REFUSAL-ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT verdict: committed
                               write_refused rows exceed kernel.refusal_seq's count -- rows
                               the write boundary's handler never counted (a forged or
                               replayed refusal row; the reconciliation is printed beside
                               s27's witness line whenever the row_hash chain itself reports
                               INTACT/EMPTY). The opposite gap (sequence > rows) is
                               EXPLAIN-grade, never a failure on its own -- its two
                               legitimate causes (a journal-INSERT double failure; a raw
                               caller's client-side rollback around the boundary function)
                               are named in the printed line. A pre-s43 world degrades
                               honestly to ORACLE-UNAVAILABLE (exit unaffected), and a
                               reconciliation query that itself fails to execute is exit 5,
                               the standing error-conflation posture.
  ./verify-chain --head      — print {world, max_id, head_hash, utc, apparatus_hash} as JSON on
                               stdout and NOTHING else — this is the input to the signed-head
                               ceremony (`./verify-chain --head > /tmp/head.json; gpg --detach-sign
                               --armor /tmp/head.json`), so its stdout must be exactly the JSON, no
                               banner lines, or a naive `cat | gpg` would sign banner text too.
                               Exit 1 (with a diagnostic on STDERR, stdout left EMPTY) if the chain
                               is not INTACT (including CANNOT-VERIFY — a capability-check query
                               failure is never grounds to sign), OR if the s27 witness reports
                               TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT or WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER, OR (2026-07-13,
                               `verify-chain-error-conflation`) if the witness check itself FAILED
                               TO RUN — signing a head over a chain the witness itself flags, or
                               couldn't even be asked about, would be worse than refusing to
                               produce one; VERIFIES the whole chain AND the witness first, always.
                               `apparatus_hash` (added 2026-07-12, tracker item
                               `apparatus-flip-witnessing` — additive to spec §4's original
                               {world, max_id, head_hash, utc} shape, not a redefinition of it) is
                               the SHA-256 of THIS world's `.claude/apparatus.json` at the moment
                               of signing, or the literal string `"absent"` if that file does not
                               exist — see `_apparatus_hash()` below. It rides inside the SAME
                               signed head, so two signed heads whose `apparatus_hash` differ PROVE
                               apparatus.json changed somewhere between them. Stated precisely, not
                               oversold: this is weaker than `head_hash`'s own guarantee, which
                               `./verify-chain` self-verifies end to end with no prior artifact
                               needed. `apparatus_hash` has no continuous chain of custody of its
                               own — proving a flip occurred means fetching two separately-signed
                               heads and comparing this field by hand (no automated two-head-diff
                               tool exists yet). What it delivers is still real and new (today,
                               comparing two heads' apparatus.json state at all is impossible) at
                               zero new infrastructure (no kernel/lineage change: this is a
                               filesystem hash folded into an operator-facing JSON object already
                               assembled here, never inside the database).

A pre-s26 world (no `row_hash` column) degrades honestly to UNAVAILABLE (not a crash, not a false
"intact") — mirrors distance-to-clean.tmpl's own pre-s22 fallback for `work_item_violations`. This
degradation is claimed ONLY when the capability-check query that determines it actually SUCCEEDED
in reporting the column absent; a query that instead fails to execute (unreachable host, refused
connection, wrong credentials, a real bug in the check itself) is CANNOT-VERIFY (exit 5), never
UNAVAILABLE (exit 0) — see `has_row_hash_layer()` / `verify()`'s own docstrings (tracker item
`verify-chain-error-conflation`, 2026-07-13: this conflation was the defect this fix closes, and it
applies identically to `has_high_water_layer()` for the s27 tail-deletion witness, one function
down).

Deployment resolution, connection posture, and path resolution mirror pickup.tmpl /
distance-to-clean.tmpl exactly (PICKUP_DEPLOYMENT, AUTOHARN, `SET ROLE <dep.role>`) — this file
executes IN PLACE out of the autoharn checkout (the "live verbs" ruling); ADR-0012 P1, one
resolution mechanism, not a fifth hand-copy.

Read-only throughout: every query here is a SELECT; this script issues no INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE.
Lazy imports banned.
"""
from __future__ import annotations

import hashlib
import json
import os
import subprocess
import sys
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from pathlib import Path

HERE = Path(__file__).resolve().parent
AUTOHARN = Path(os.environ.get("AUTOHARN", str(HERE / ".." / ".."))).resolve()
DEPLOYMENT_PATH = Path(os.environ.get("PICKUP_DEPLOYMENT", str(HERE / "deployment.json")))

# Round-3 review ROOT CAUSE fix (discharges the standing row-1159 residual for this verb, the
# same treatment audit.tmpl got in round 2): intercept --help/-h HERE, before deployment.json is
# ever touched. Without this, main() called _load_deployment() unconditionally -- argv was only
# inspected for `--head` mode, never for --help -- so a deployment-less checkout's `--help`
# produced the SAME shared "deployment record not found ... pickup, judge, and led alike"
# refusal every OTHER deployment-resolving verb produces, with no marker naming 'verify-chain'
# anywhere (a dispatch-parity hazard: a wrong-target dispatch landing on this verb would look
# identical to the real one). This is a real, side-effect-free usage line naming this verb,
# printed and exited BEFORE deployment_record is even imported.
if any(a in ("--help", "-h") for a in sys.argv[1:]):
    print(
        "usage: verify-chain [--head]\n"
        "\n"
        "verify-chain -- Rung 3 of design/MAINT-GPG-TRUST-LAYER.md §4: walks this world's\n"
        "row_hash chain (kernel/lineage/s26-row-hash-chain.sql) end to end and reports the\n"
        "first row (if any) whose stored row_hash disagrees with a fresh recomputation, cross-\n"
        "checked against the s27 chain_high_water tail-deletion witness and the s43\n"
        "refusal-record completeness oracle.\n"
        "\n"
        "  (no args)   walk the chain; print INTACT/EMPTY/UNAVAILABLE/CANNOT-VERIFY/BROKEN plus\n"
        "              the witness/oracle lines. Exit 0 intact+witnesses-agree, 1 BROKEN,\n"
        "              3 TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT, 4 WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER, 5 CANNOT-VERIFY (a\n"
        "              capability-check query itself failed to execute), 6\n"
        "              REFUSAL-ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT\n"
        "  --head      print {world, max_id, head_hash, utc, apparatus_hash} as JSON on stdout\n"
        "              ONLY (the signed-head ceremony's input) -- refuses (exit 1, stdout\n"
        "              empty) unless the chain and both witnesses are clean\n"
        "\n"
        "Read-only throughout; this summary itself needs neither a reachable Postgres host nor\n"
        "a parsed deployment.json -- see this file's own top-of-file comment for full detail."
    )
    sys.exit(0)

sys.path.insert(0, str(AUTOHARN / "filing"))
try:
    import deployment_record  # noqa: E402  (filing/deployment_record.py, the ONE home for the shape)
except ImportError as _e:
    print(f"verify-chain: cannot import autoharn's filing/deployment_record.py under "
          f"AUTOHARN={AUTOHARN} ({_e.__class__.__name__}: {_e})", file=sys.stderr)
    print("        set AUTOHARN=/path/to/autoharn, or place a sibling checkout at ../autoharn", file=sys.stderr)
    sys.exit(2)


def _load_deployment():
    try:
        return deployment_record.load_deployment(DEPLOYMENT_PATH)
    except deployment_record.DeploymentError as e:
        print(f"verify-chain: {e}", file=sys.stderr)
        sys.exit(2)


def _apparatus_hash() -> str:
    """SHA-256 (hex) of `.claude/apparatus.json`'s raw bytes for THIS world (tracker item
    `apparatus-flip-witnessing`, 2026-07-12 -- the panel finding that a flip of apparatus.json
    between two signed chain heads was otherwise undetectable: the row_hash chain above covers
    only ledger rows, never this filesystem config file). Project root is `DEPLOYMENT_PATH.parent`,
    NOT `HERE` -- this script executes IN PLACE out of the autoharn checkout (module docstring), so
    `HERE` is the autoharn tree, while `DEPLOYMENT_PATH` (env-overridden by every scaffolded
    world's `verify-chain` shim to `$PROJECT_ROOT/deployment.json`) is the one value that reliably
    resolves to THIS world's own root. Returns the literal string `"absent"` -- never a real
    64-hex-char digest, so a reader can never mistake "no apparatus.json" for "some hash" -- when
    the file does not exist or cannot be read; never raises."""
    path = DEPLOYMENT_PATH.parent / ".claude" / "apparatus.json"
    try:
        raw = path.read_bytes()
    except OSError:
        return "absent"
    return hashlib.sha256(raw).hexdigest()


def _psql_json_rows(dep, sql: str) -> tuple[list[dict] | None, str]:
    """Returns (rows, error). rows is None on a query error (error carries psql's stderr);
    rows is [] for an empty result. Uses `jsonb_agg` (not `json_agg`): `json_agg` preserves
    `ROW(...)`'s original whitespace, which Postgres renders with a newline between array
    elements -- exactly the kind of multi-line-output-mistaken-for-one-line bug pickup.tmpl's
    own `_last_stmt_rows` quirk warns about one level up. `jsonb_agg` normalizes to compact,
    single-line JSON, so the "drop the leading SET-ROLE echo line, the rest is the payload"
    convention this project's other verbs already use (distance-to-clean.tmpl's
    `_last_stmt_rows`) holds here without a second-line-only bug."""
    full = (f"SET ROLE {dep.role};\n"
            f"SELECT coalesce(jsonb_agg(t), '[]'::jsonb) FROM ({sql}) t;")
    r = subprocess.run(["psql", "-h", dep.host, "-d", dep.db, "-t", "-A", "-v", "ON_ERROR_STOP=1",
                        "-c", full], capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=30)
    if r.returncode != 0:
        return None, r.stderr.strip()
    lines = [ln for ln in r.stdout.strip("\n").splitlines() if ln.strip()]
    body = lines[1] if len(lines) > 1 else (lines[0] if lines else "[]")
    return json.loads(body), ""


def has_row_hash_layer(dep) -> tuple[bool | None, str]:
    """An EXPLICIT capability check (information_schema), never a fuzzy match on error text --
    a real query bug (a typo, a missing schema qualification) OR a connection failure (refused,
    auth failed, timeout) must surface as its own loud verdict, never be silently miscategorized
    as the honest pre-s26 UNAVAILABLE case.

    Returns (present, err), mirroring `_psql_json_rows`' own (rows, err) convention so the two
    world-states it distinguishes cannot be collapsed by the caller: `present` is True/False when
    the capability-check query itself SUCCEEDED (a genuine schema answer -- the honest case, either
    polarity); `present` is None when the query FAILED TO EXECUTE at all (`err` carries psql's
    stderr verbatim) -- we never got an answer, so the caller must never read that as "answer: no".
    (tracker item `verify-chain-error-conflation`, 2026-07-13: before this fix, `bool(None)` -- i.e.
    a connection refusal or auth failure on THIS query -- silently evaluated to `False`, which the
    one caller (`verify()`) read as "table absent, honest pre-s26 world", exactly the conflation
    this function's own docstring already promised never to commit.)"""
    sql = (f"SELECT count(*) FROM information_schema.columns WHERE table_schema = '{dep.schema}' "
           f"AND table_name = 'ledger' AND column_name = 'row_hash'")
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, f"SELECT ({sql}) > 0 AS present")
    if rows is None:
        return None, err
    return (bool(rows) and rows[0].get("present") is True), ""


def walk_chain(dep) -> tuple[list[dict] | None, str]:
    """Walks every ledger row that CARRIES a row_hash. This is `WHERE l.row_hash IS NOT NULL`,
    not `ORDER BY l.id` over the whole table unconditionally -- added 2026-07-15, tracker item
    s26-accommodation-build, MID-HISTORY CHAIN START: a world migrated in place via
    kernel/lineage/s26-row-hash-chain.accommodate.sql legitimately carries pre-migration-epoch
    rows with NULL row_hash (exempt by type, never backfilled -- see that file's own header).
    Before this fix, walking ALL rows unconditionally computed an "expected" hash for every
    pre-epoch row too and compared it against its (always NULL) `stored` value -- ALWAYS a
    mismatch, so a migrated world's chain reported BROKEN at row 1 with EVERY row flagged,
    witnessed directly rehearsing this build's own accommodation against a byte-faithful clone of
    real autoharn1 history (997/997 rows "mismatched"). The predecessor-hash subquery below is
    UNCHANGED and does not need to be: it already looks at the row IMMEDIATELY preceding `l.id`
    (regardless of that predecessor's own null-ness) and COALESCEs a NULL predecessor hash to the
    genesis seed -- which is exactly what the live `zz_set_row_hash` trigger itself does (it reads
    "the last row" unconditionally, not "the last row with a hash"), so the first WALKED
    (post-epoch) row's expected predecessor is correctly the genesis seed whenever the row
    immediately before it is a pre-epoch, NULL-row_hash row -- the natural, mid-chain-start
    equivalent of a birth-chain world's very first row. A birth-chain world has no pre-epoch rows
    at all, so this filter is a no-op there -- identical behavior to before this fix."""
    sql = (f"SELECT l.id, l.row_hash AS stored, "
           f"{dep.schema}.compute_row_hash(l, COALESCE("
           f"(SELECT p.row_hash FROM {dep.schema}.ledger p WHERE p.id < l.id ORDER BY p.id DESC LIMIT 1), "
           f"(SELECT seed FROM {dep.kern}.chain_genesis LIMIT 1))) AS expected "
           f"FROM {dep.schema}.ledger l WHERE l.row_hash IS NOT NULL ORDER BY l.id")
    return _psql_json_rows(dep, sql)


def count_pre_epoch_exempt_rows(dep) -> int | None:
    """Rows with NULL row_hash that `walk_chain` correctly skips -- reported alongside the walk
    result purely as EVIDENCE (never affects the exit code) so an operator reading verify-chain's
    output on a migrated world sees the skip was deliberate, not silent. Returns None (never
    raises) if the count query itself fails -- advisory only, mirrors `sequence_last_value`'s own
    fail-open posture; the count is corroboration, not a claim this function is depended on for."""
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, f"SELECT count(*) AS n FROM {dep.schema}.ledger "
                                      f"WHERE row_hash IS NULL")
    if not rows:
        return None
    return rows[0].get("n")


def verify(dep) -> tuple[str, dict]:
    """Returns (status, detail). status in {INTACT, BROKEN, UNAVAILABLE, ERROR, EMPTY,
    CANNOT-VERIFY}.

    CANNOT-VERIFY (added 2026-07-13, tracker item `verify-chain-error-conflation`) is a DISTINCT
    world-state from UNAVAILABLE, never conflated with it: UNAVAILABLE means the has_row_hash_layer
    capability-check query SUCCEEDED and genuinely found no row_hash column (the honest pre-s26
    case -- this world predates kernel delta s26, nothing to verify, not an error). CANNOT-VERIFY
    means that SAME query FAILED TO EXECUTE (connection refused, auth failed, timeout, a real query
    bug) -- we never looked at the schema at all, so reporting the benign pre-s26 absence would be
    lying about having looked. A verifier that cannot connect must say so loudly, not shrug and
    call it "nothing to verify here"."""
    present, probe_err = has_row_hash_layer(dep)
    if present is None:
        return "CANNOT-VERIFY", {"reason": (
            "could not determine whether kernel/lineage/s26-row-hash-chain.sql is applied here -- "
            f"the has_row_hash_layer() capability-check query itself failed to execute (this is NOT "
            f"a schema answer, and must never be read as one): {probe_err}")}
    if not present:
        return "UNAVAILABLE", {"reason": ("pre-s26 kernel -- no row_hash chain in schema "
                                           f"{dep.schema} (kernel/lineage/s26-row-hash-chain.sql "
                                           "not applied here)")}
    rows, err = walk_chain(dep)
    if rows is None:
        return "ERROR", {"reason": err}
    exempt = count_pre_epoch_exempt_rows(dep)
    if not rows:
        return "EMPTY", {"reason": "no ledger rows yet", "pre_epoch_exempt_rows": exempt}
    breaks = [r for r in rows if r["stored"] != r["expected"]]
    if breaks:
        first = breaks[0]
        return "BROKEN", {"first_break_id": first["id"], "stored": first["stored"],
                           "expected": first["expected"], "total_breaks": len(breaks),
                           "rows_walked": len(rows), "pre_epoch_exempt_rows": exempt}
    return "INTACT", {"rows_walked": len(rows), "head_id": rows[-1]["id"], "head_hash": rows[-1]["stored"],
                       "pre_epoch_exempt_rows": exempt}


def has_high_water_layer(dep) -> tuple[bool | None, str]:
    """An EXPLICIT capability check (information_schema), mirroring has_row_hash_layer()'s own
    posture and its (present, err) return shape (never a fuzzy match on error text, never a
    collapsed boolean): a real query bug or connection failure must surface as its own loud ERROR
    verdict (see compare_witness()), never be silently miscategorized as the honest pre-s27
    WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE case just because the query returned no rows. `present` is None when the
    query itself failed to execute (`err` carries psql's stderr); same conflation, same fix, one
    function down (tracker item `verify-chain-error-conflation`, 2026-07-13)."""
    sql = (f"SELECT count(*) FROM information_schema.tables WHERE table_schema = '{dep.kern}' "
           f"AND table_name = 'chain_high_water'")
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, f"SELECT ({sql}) > 0 AS present")
    if rows is None:
        return None, err
    return (bool(rows) and rows[0].get("present") is True), ""


def read_high_water(dep) -> tuple[int | None, str]:
    """Returns (max_id, error). max_id is None if the table exists but carries no row (should not
    happen via bootstrap/new-project.sh's own idempotent seeding -- s27's DDL inserts the
    singleton row itself -- but degraded honestly rather than assumed impossible)."""
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, f"SELECT max_id FROM {dep.kern}.chain_high_water LIMIT 1")
    if rows is None:
        return None, err
    if not rows:
        return None, ""
    return rows[0]["max_id"], ""


def sequence_last_value(dep) -> int | None:
    """SECONDARY, explain-not-fail corroboration only (s27's own header): the bigserial sequence
    backing ledger.id, read via pg_sequences (no special privilege needed -- it is a system
    catalog view, readable by any role). Returns None on any failure -- this reading is advisory
    and must never itself cause an ERROR/non-zero exit; the primary witness is chain_high_water."""
    sql = (f"SELECT last_value FROM pg_sequences WHERE schemaname = '{dep.schema}' "
           f"AND sequencename = 'ledger_id_seq'")
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, sql)
    if not rows:
        return None
    return rows[0].get("last_value")


def compare_witness(dep, walked_max_id: int) -> tuple[str, dict]:
    """Returns (status, detail). status in {TAIL-COVERAGE-CONFIRMED, TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT,
    WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER, WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE, ERROR}. walked_max_id is the highest id actually
    seen by the row_hash walk (0 for an EMPTY chain -- no row ever walked, so there is nothing to
    be missing from the tail yet)."""
    present, probe_err = has_high_water_layer(dep)
    if present is None:
        return "ERROR", {"reason": (
            "could not determine whether kernel/lineage/s27-chain-high-water.sql is applied here "
            f"-- the has_high_water_layer() capability-check query itself failed to execute (this "
            f"is NOT a schema answer, and must never be read as the honest pre-s27 "
            f"WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE case): {probe_err}")}
    if not present:
        return "WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE", {
            "reason": ("pre-s27 kernel -- no chain_high_water witness in "
                       f"{dep.kern} (kernel/lineage/s27-chain-high-water.sql not applied here); "
                       "tail-deletion coverage cannot be claimed for this world")}
    witness_max, err = read_high_water(dep)
    if err:
        return "ERROR", {"reason": err}
    if witness_max is None:
        return "WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE", {
            "reason": (f"{dep.kern}.chain_high_water carries no row -- s27 applied without its "
                       "singleton row seeded (should not happen via bootstrap/new-project.sh's "
                       "own idempotent DDL); tail-deletion coverage cannot be claimed")}
    if witness_max == walked_max_id:
        return "TAIL-COVERAGE-CONFIRMED", {"witness_max_id": witness_max, "walked_max_id": walked_max_id}
    if witness_max > walked_max_id:
        return "TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT", {
            "witness_max_id": witness_max, "walked_max_id": walked_max_id,
            "missing_count": witness_max - walked_max_id}
    return "WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER", {
        "witness_max_id": witness_max, "walked_max_id": walked_max_id,
        "reason": ("the witness max_id is LOWER than the highest surviving ledger id -- "
                   "structurally should never happen under correct operation (the witness only "
                   "bumps upward, in the same transaction as each insert); this indicates the "
                   "witness itself was altered outside its trigger (a schema-owner-level act, "
                   "the same adversary class s26/s27's own LIMITS sections already name) or was "
                   "reset/reseeded incorrectly for this world")}


def _witness_note(dep, status: str, detail: dict) -> tuple[str, str, dict]:
    """Runs the s27 witness comparison for the two hash-chain statuses where it is meaningful
    (INTACT / EMPTY -- the row_hash chain itself claims no interior tamper, so a tail deletion is
    the one remaining gap it cannot see) and returns (line-to-print, witness_status, witness_detail).
    For BROKEN/UNAVAILABLE/ERROR the row_hash chain has ALREADY reported a problem through its own
    channel; the witness check is explicitly SKIPPED (never silently omitted -- the skip is its
    own printed line) rather than layered on top of an already-diagnosed chain."""
    if status not in ("INTACT", "EMPTY"):
        return (f"verify-chain: tail-deletion witness check SKIPPED -- hash-chain status is "
                f"{status}, already diagnosed above", "SKIPPED", {})
    walked_max_id = detail["head_id"] if status == "INTACT" else 0
    w_status, w_detail = compare_witness(dep, walked_max_id)
    seq_last = sequence_last_value(dep)
    seq_note = (f" (secondary corroboration: ledger_id_seq.last_value={seq_last}, "
                f"explain-not-fail -- nextval() is non-transactional and does not roll back on "
                f"an aborted insert, so this figure alone would false-positive on any world that "
                f"ever rolled back a write)" if seq_last is not None else "")
    if w_status == "WITNESS-UNAVAILABLE":
        return (f"verify-chain: tail-deletion witness UNAVAILABLE -- {w_detail['reason']}",
                w_status, w_detail)
    if w_status == "ERROR":
        return (f"verify-chain: tail-deletion witness ERROR -- {w_detail['reason']}", w_status, w_detail)
    if w_status == "TAIL-COVERAGE-CONFIRMED":
        return (f"verify-chain: TAIL-COVERAGE-CONFIRMED -- witness max_id="
                f"{w_detail['witness_max_id']} agrees with walked max_id="
                f"{w_detail['walked_max_id']}{seq_note}", w_status, w_detail)
    if w_status == "TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT":
        return (f"verify-chain: TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT -- witness max_id="
                f"{w_detail['witness_max_id']} is AHEAD of the walked max_id="
                f"{w_detail['walked_max_id']} ({w_detail['missing_count']} row(s) missing from "
                f"the tail; the row_hash chain alone cannot see this -- s27's own witness is "
                f"what caught it){seq_note}", w_status, w_detail)
    # WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER
    return (f"verify-chain: WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER (anomaly) -- witness max_id="
            f"{w_detail['witness_max_id']} is BEHIND the walked max_id={w_detail['walked_max_id']}: "
            f"{w_detail['reason']}{seq_note}", w_status, w_detail)


def has_refusal_layer(dep) -> tuple[bool | None, str]:
    """An EXPLICIT capability check for the s43 refusal-recording layer (kernel/lineage/
    s43-typed-verdict-write-boundary.sql Element 5), mirroring has_high_water_layer()'s own
    posture and (present, err) shape exactly: `present` is True/False when the query itself
    SUCCEEDED (a genuine schema answer -- the honest pre-s43 case reads False, never an
    error); None when it FAILED TO EXECUTE (`err` carries psql's stderr) -- never read as
    "answer: no" (the verify-chain-error-conflation lesson, one layer over)."""
    sql = (f"SELECT count(*) FROM information_schema.sequences WHERE sequence_schema = "
           f"'{dep.kern}' AND sequence_name = 'refusal_seq'")
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, f"SELECT ({sql}) > 0 AS present")
    if rows is None:
        return None, err
    return (bool(rows) and rows[0].get("present") is True), ""


def reconcile_refusal_oracle(dep) -> tuple[str, dict]:
    """The s43 refusal-record completeness reconciliation (spec
    design/FABLE-REFUSAL-RECORDING-AND-HASH-COVERAGE-SPEC.md §4.6; the flaw-1 second-witness
    demand): compares count(*) of committed write_refused rows against kernel.refusal_seq --
    the non-transactional counter the write boundary's journaler bumps immediately BEFORE
    each journal INSERT, which no rollback erases and the subject role cannot advance
    (SELECT-only grant). Returns (status, detail); status in:
      ORACLE-CONFIRMED       count == sequence: every counted refusal is a committed row and
                             every committed refusal row was counted.
      ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT count > sequence: FAIL-grade -- refusal rows exist the handler
                             never counted (forged or replayed write_refused rows; the §4.2
                             forgery-channel tripwire).
      ORACLE-GAP-EXPLAINED   sequence > count: EXPLAIN-grade, never a failure on its own --
                             the two legitimate causes are named in the detail (a
                             journal-INSERT double failure, which also aborted loudly at the
                             time; or a raw caller wrapping the boundary function in a
                             transaction it then rolled back -- the CLI never wraps).
      ORACLE-UNAVAILABLE     pre-s43 kernel: no refusal_seq (an honest capability answer).
      ERROR                  a query itself failed to execute -- never conflated with any of
                             the above (the standing error-conflation posture)."""
    present, probe_err = has_refusal_layer(dep)
    if present is None:
        return "ERROR", {"reason": (
            "could not determine whether kernel/lineage/s43-typed-verdict-write-boundary.sql "
            f"is applied here -- the has_refusal_layer() capability-check query itself failed "
            f"to execute (NOT a schema answer): {probe_err}")}
    if not present:
        return "ORACLE-UNAVAILABLE", {
            "reason": ("pre-s43 kernel -- no refusal_seq oracle in "
                       f"{dep.kern} (kernel/lineage/s43-typed-verdict-write-boundary.sql not "
                       "applied here); refusal-record completeness cannot be claimed for this "
                       "world")}
    rows, err = _psql_json_rows(dep, (
        f"SELECT (SELECT count(*) FROM {dep.schema}.ledger WHERE kind = 'write_refused') "
        f"AS journaled, "
        f"(SELECT CASE WHEN s.is_called THEN s.last_value ELSE 0 END "
        f" FROM {dep.kern}.refusal_seq s) AS counted"))
    if rows is None or not rows:
        return "ERROR", {"reason": err or "empty reconciliation result"}
    journaled, counted = rows[0]["journaled"], rows[0]["counted"]
    if journaled == counted:
        return "ORACLE-CONFIRMED", {"journaled_rows": journaled, "sequence_count": counted}
    if journaled > counted:
        return "ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT", {
            "journaled_rows": journaled, "sequence_count": counted,
            "excess": journaled - counted,
            "reason": ("MORE committed write_refused rows than the handler ever counted -- "
                       "the boundary's journaler bumps the sequence before every journal "
                       "INSERT, so an uncounted refusal row was written by something OTHER "
                       "than the handler (a forged or replayed refusal row; the s43 §4.2 "
                       "forgery-channel tripwire)")}
    return "ORACLE-GAP-EXPLAINED", {
        "journaled_rows": journaled, "sequence_count": counted,
        "gap": counted - journaled,
        "reason": ("the sequence counted refusals that have no committed row -- legitimate "
                   "causes, named (spec §4.6/§8): (a) a journal-INSERT double failure (which "
                   "also aborted loudly at the time; the server log holds the statement), or "
                   "(b) a raw caller wrapping the boundary function in a transaction it then "
                   "rolled back, discarding the refusal row after the non-transactional bump "
                   "(the CLI never wraps). EXPLAIN-grade, not a failure on its own -- the "
                   "one-directional honesty of a rollback-proof counter")}


def _refusal_note(dep) -> tuple[str, str]:
    """One printed line for the refusal-oracle reconciliation, mirroring _witness_note's own
    shape one witness over. Runs unconditionally (unlike the tail witness it does not depend
    on the walk's head id)."""
    status, detail = reconcile_refusal_oracle(dep)
    if status == "ORACLE-UNAVAILABLE":
        return (f"verify-chain: refusal-record oracle UNAVAILABLE -- {detail['reason']}",
                status)
    if status == "ERROR":
        return (f"verify-chain: refusal-record oracle ERROR -- {detail['reason']}", status)
    if status == "ORACLE-CONFIRMED":
        return (f"verify-chain: REFUSAL-ORACLE-CONFIRMED -- {detail['journaled_rows']} "
                f"journaled write_refused row(s) == sequence count "
                f"{detail['sequence_count']} (kernel.refusal_seq, the rollback-proof "
                f"counter -- s43's completeness witness)", status)
    if status == "ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT":
        return (f"verify-chain: REFUSAL-ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT -- {detail['journaled_rows']} "
                f"journaled write_refused row(s) but the sequence only counted "
                f"{detail['sequence_count']} ({detail['excess']} uncounted row(s)): "
                f"{detail['reason']}", status)
    return (f"verify-chain: refusal-record oracle GAP, explained -- sequence counted "
            f"{detail['sequence_count']}, committed rows {detail['journaled_rows']} "
            f"({detail['gap']} discarded): {detail['reason']}", status)


def main(argv: list[str]) -> int:
    head_mode = "--head" in argv
    dep = _load_deployment()
    status, detail = verify(dep)

    if head_mode:
        if status != "INTACT":
            print(f"verify-chain --head: REFUSED -- chain is not INTACT (status={status}, "
                  f"{detail}); signing a head over a non-verified chain is refused, not attempted.",
                  file=sys.stderr)
            return 1
        w_status, w_detail = compare_witness(dep, detail["head_id"])
        if w_status in ("TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT", "WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER"):
            print(f"verify-chain --head: REFUSED -- tail-deletion witness reports {w_status} "
                  f"({w_detail}); signing a head over a chain the witness itself flags is refused, "
                  f"not attempted -- exactly the same posture as refusing on a BROKEN row_hash "
                  f"chain, applied to the gap that chain alone cannot see.", file=sys.stderr)
            return 1
        if w_status == "ERROR":
            # Fixed alongside verify-chain-error-conflation (2026-07-13): before this, an ERROR
            # here (has_high_water_layer or read_high_water's query failing to execute -- e.g. a
            # connection drop between the row_hash walk and the witness check) fell through this
            # `if` untouched and proceeded to SIGN a head whose witness was never actually
            # consulted -- silently as strong a claim as TAIL-COVERAGE-CONFIRMED. A query failure
            # must refuse the signing, exactly like a witness that actively flags a problem.
            print(f"verify-chain --head: REFUSED -- tail-deletion witness check FAILED TO RUN "
                  f"({w_detail}); signing a head when the witness itself could not be consulted is "
                  f"refused, not attempted -- never silently treated as if the witness agreed.",
                  file=sys.stderr)
            return 1
        r_line, r_status = _refusal_note(dep)
        if r_status == "ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT":
            print(f"verify-chain --head: REFUSED -- the s43 refusal-record oracle reports "
                  f"FORGERY-SUSPECT ({r_line}); signing a head over a chain carrying "
                  f"write_refused rows the handler never counted is refused, not attempted -- "
                  f"the same posture as a BROKEN chain, applied to the completeness witness.",
                  file=sys.stderr)
            return 1
        if r_status == "ERROR":
            print(f"verify-chain --head: REFUSED -- the s43 refusal-record oracle check "
                  f"FAILED TO RUN ({r_line}); signing a head when a witness could not be "
                  f"consulted is refused, never silently treated as if it agreed.",
                  file=sys.stderr)
            return 1
        head = {"world": dep.name or dep.schema, "max_id": detail["head_id"],
                "head_hash": detail["head_hash"],
                "utc": datetime.now(timezone.utc).strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),
                "apparatus_hash": _apparatus_hash()}
        print(json.dumps(head))  # ONLY the JSON on stdout -- see module docstring
        return 0

    witness_line, witness_status, _ = _witness_note(dep, status, detail)

    if status == "INTACT":
        exempt_note = (f", {detail['pre_epoch_exempt_rows']} pre-migration-epoch row(s) exempt "
                        f"by type (NULL row_hash, skipped -- kernel/lineage/"
                        f"s26-row-hash-chain.accommodate.sql)"
                        if detail.get("pre_epoch_exempt_rows") else "")
        print(f"verify-chain: INTACT -- {detail['rows_walked']} row(s) walked, head id="
              f"{detail['head_id']} hash={detail['head_hash']}{exempt_note}")
        print(witness_line)
        refusal_line, refusal_status = _refusal_note(dep)
        print(refusal_line)
        if refusal_status == "ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT":
            return 6
        if witness_status == "TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT":
            return 3
        if witness_status == "WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER":
            return 4
        if refusal_status == "ERROR":
            return 5
        if witness_status == "ERROR":
            # Fixed alongside verify-chain-error-conflation (2026-07-13): before this fix, a
            # witness-level query failure (has_high_water_layer or read_high_water erroring, e.g.
            # a connection drop mid-run) fell through every branch above to `return 0` -- the SAME
            # exit code as a fully-confirmed witness, even though `witness_line` above already
            # prints the failure. A query failure the operator only sees by reading stdout text is
            # not loud enough (ADR-0002); the exit code must say so too.
            return 5
        return 0
    if status == "EMPTY":
        print(f"verify-chain: EMPTY -- {detail['reason']} (an empty chain is trivially intact; "
              f"nothing to walk)")
        print(witness_line)
        refusal_line, refusal_status = _refusal_note(dep)
        print(refusal_line)
        if refusal_status == "ORACLE-FORGERY-SUSPECT":
            return 6
        if witness_status == "TAIL-DELETION-SUSPECT":
            return 3
        if witness_status == "WITNESS-BEHIND-LEDGER":
            return 4
        if refusal_status == "ERROR":
            return 5
        if witness_status == "ERROR":
            return 5
        return 0
    if status == "UNAVAILABLE":
        print(f"verify-chain: UNAVAILABLE -- {detail['reason']}")
        print(witness_line)
        return 0
    if status == "CANNOT-VERIFY":
        # Distinct from UNAVAILABLE by construction (verify()'s own docstring): this is the
        # has_row_hash_layer() capability-check query itself failing to execute -- connection
        # refused, auth failed, timeout, or a real query bug -- never the honest pre-s26 absence.
        # Its own exit code (5), never conflated with UNAVAILABLE's 0 or BROKEN's 1.
        print(f"verify-chain: CANNOT-VERIFY -- {detail['reason']}")
        print(witness_line)
        return 5
    if status == "BROKEN":
        print(f"verify-chain: BROKEN -- first break at row id {detail['first_break_id']}:")
        print(f"    stored:   {detail['stored']}")
        print(f"    expected: {detail['expected']}")
        print(f"  ({detail['total_breaks']} of {detail['rows_walked']} row(s) mismatch total. "
              f"The FIRST break is where alteration is provably detectable: either the altered "
              f"row's own content no longer matches its OWN stored hash (tamper left the stored "
              f"row_hash stale, the common case), or -- if the tamperer also rewrote that row's "
              f"row_hash to match its new content -- the NEXT row breaks instead, because its "
              f"predecessor-hash reference was computed against the row's OLD, honest hash. "
              f"Either way, the break can be no later than immediately after the true alteration "
              f"point; it is never silently absorbed further downstream than that.)")
        print(witness_line)
        return 1
    print(f"verify-chain: ERROR -- {detail['reason']}", file=sys.stderr)
    return 2


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main(sys.argv[1:]))
